<font color="#FF0000">COGNITIVE DISSIDENCE</font><br>
<tt>Tue May  6  9:50:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This is a follow-up to Doc Del's original question concerning my views on compromising one's beliefs and the inherent stress that this situation brings about.  When a person acts consistently with his/her belief system, there is no real mental stress.  When one acts outside one's belief system, there is what mental health professionals call &quot;cognitive dissidence,&quot; or inharmonious thinking.  In other words, and &quot;doc&quot; Spatz you can help me out on this, the person is at war with him/herself.  <br><br>
In my case, because all of my actions were consistent with my own beliefs, I suffered very little stress from my participation in Vietnam.  Our unit, the 37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron, saved lives.  We were not there to take lives.  <br><br>
In Doc Del's case, I cannot say.  Each individual has a different reaction to the various circumstances that they encounter.  <br><br>
It seems that for every action, or inaction, there is a price to pay.  My decision to go to Vietnam had less of a price than my decision to join the Air Force.  My decision to get out of the Air Force also had a price, as I wasn't the same person, and retained my service links through the USAF Reserves.  It was the same career field, but different people--people who choose the Reserves to stay out of Vietnam.  In school, I related as a student, but still had service connections.  This led to what I believed was some discrimination, both at school and at a summer job I took.  <br><br>
It seems that we all, at one point or another, compromise to please an important person.  If we compromise so much as to compromise basic beliefs, then we are in for some mental anguish.  Likewise, if we undertake a mission for the USA and then find that we've been lied to about the basic nature of the mission, then the deceit can cause problems if it makes us do something we do not believe in.  <br><br>
But for those of us who volunteered for a humanitarian mission, and went in with our eyes open, the mental adjustment was not great.  <br><br>
When we returned home to the types of reactions we sometimes received, that's when the stress became higher.<br>

